segments.text: He became active that early then?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, he was active.
He never was president of the association during my tenure, but he became president of the association shortly after Buck came in.
Was he positive regarding these changes?
I don't think he was real positive to start with.
That would have been my guess.
Yes.
I think he was more on Earl's side.
than anybody, but I think he, it came around, okay, was Royce.

You were asking the big posers of that, the Beaumont A&M Club through Charlie Babcock's influence, and the Houston A&M Club to some extent through the influence of Mr. Travis Smith, and the A&M Mothers Club as a group,
They didn't want any of the old traditions changed.
But beyond that, the Aggies I think generally were positively responsive to the changes.
You mentioned those two that have a little bit of a regional Beaumont and Houston, but by and large it wasn't engineers for and ag against.
It didn't break down that way, did it?
No, it didn't break down.
No, it didn't break down by
agriculture or engineers or anything like that.
No, it was just the breaking of a tradition.
There was no nothing like that.
Let's see.
We mentioned Hubert and...
I'm trying to think of some of those people.
Back in the early times when Earl first came back here,
Well, I remember John Calhoun and Bob Kamm.
Kamm took the place of Dean Pitberg.
And John Calhoun, I'm not sure what his first position was.
Was it Dean of Engineering?
I think so.
Okay, Dean of Engineering.
Frank Hubert came back as Dean of Arts and Sciences.
Dr. Bowden probably was here as dean of veterinary medicine.
And agriculture.
Patterson, I think.
Dr. R.E.
Patterson, and then, who was it?
Begins with an A.
Still.
Begins with an A. Yeah.
Why can't my brain recall?
Agriculture?
Wasn't Kunkel?
No.
Before Coco.
Before Coco.
I thought I had it written on some card in here.
It was an A.
Mount Shepardson.
No, no.
Gus Watkins.
Wrong.
Gus Watkins.
Gus Watkins, yeah.
Gus Watkins.
I was wrong on that.
Yeah, Gus Watkins.
I remember Gus.
And I, now, as far as you... Now, let me think a minute.
I had my mind on two other people.
One of the things that pleased Earl most back in that era was to be able to persuade these two chemists to come here from Pittsburgh or somewhere up there.
Well, Zwolinski.
and his partner.
I can't think of the name of his partner because he died a long time ago.
He died in 64 or 65.
But they came down here from some chemical institute, Carnegie Tech or somewhere.
And they were outstanding chemists and that was the beginning of trying to recruit some of the top people.
course later on they got Zener and they got this doctor that was in physics.
Well I remember Mr.
Rudder saying sometimes when outstanding people were hired away from here, we're proud to have had them.
And a few of us cynics at first thought that he was meaning well you know we're glad somebody else paid him more money.
Then we realized no he was he was really saying we're glad that it
that we're one of the places where the top schools- We've had them as long as we did.
Yeah.
Who are some other former students that you think deserve credit for helping A&M move forward from your experience?
Well, I think, of course I've mentioned the top ones that I've been talking about.
Dr. Harold Dunn, Jimmy Askins, Maggie McGee, John Mangus.
And then the Weisenbakers.
Royce Weisenbaker is the one that started the endowed presidential scholarship program.
He put up the first one in Earl's name.
Put up one in Buck's name.
The Pete Petersons, only I disagreed with Pete.
Pete disagreed with me on several things.
Still, Pete was the president of the association.
He later was a member of the board of directors of the institution, later a member of the board of coordinating boards.
Pete Peterson and John Younger from West Texas.
Let me tell you about a meeting we had with John Younger.
John Younger, you can see the problem.
As you probably know, A&M student body was called Mickey Mouse in those days.
Aggies would go home and strut those boots up and down the halls with a shaved head and the students would lie down.
And John Young called me and said, you'll get Earl and you'll come to Midland.
I want to have a luncheon.
It's not going to be the A&M Club, it's going to be me eating on the school board in Midland.
He said, I want to have a luncheon.
And I want to have the school superintendent and the high school principal present.
And we're going to have a frank discussion.
I remember with Maggie.
Maggie and and I sat there and had a luncheon.
And Earl.
And Earl was more or less new at the job at the time.
So it would have been in 58 or maybe 58.
Before all this century business, aspirations and all that, we went to this country club in Midland.
This superintendent and this president got to talk about A&M.
These two men just told Earl just like he was.
He said, Earl, I don't know, you don't realize it, I'm sure, but when these kids from A&M come to Midland, all these other kids laugh at them.
And when you talk to these students in middle and high school about going to A&M, they just laugh.
They're not about to go to A&M.
They want to go to Texas Tech.
They want to go to the University of Texas.
Or they want to go to these teachers' colleges out there.
They don't want to go to A&M.
And Earl was in state shock.
He said, why?
He said, well, it's all Mickey Mouse stuff.
He said, these kids don't like the military.
They don't like the regimentation.
They don't like to go to a place where they don't grow.
Particularly, a place like Pratt & Kelly Station, or El Paso, where they can have some social stuff.
where they don't have to wear a uniform.
They don't want to wear a uniform.
Earl just tore Earl's heart out to say not to wear a uniform.
But they were so honest.
And I really left there feeling sorry for Earl because they were so right.
They were so honest and so right.
And I think that was the first time that Earl had been talked to like that by somebody that was totally neutral.
And really, trying to do what was best for him.
And John Younger, you see, he knew as well as those administrators what was happening.
And so I had to put John Younger in the way of what was best.
Of course, I told you a little bit about John and Jen, which is somewhat the same for Fort Auburn.
They wouldn't keep right along.
President of the Association and then went on to be a member of the Board of Directors and was active and strong.
I really, I don't know whether I'm getting older or whether I've been away from it longer, but I don't see the kind of legals
in the associations program that I remember he had.

All right, as a person who's been away from A&M for 17 years, now back two, I agree with you in the events that I've attended here and elsewhere, I don't see people that I would call major league status in the association leadership like there used to be.
That's the point.
When I left, though,
But I lived over there and I was partially responsible for Buck getting that job.
And I sat down with Buck and I said, Buck, let me tell you what I think is the most important function that you have.
And that function is the kind of people that you seek out to be your leaders.
And I said, don't settle for the lower echelon.
If you're going to get somebody from Houston, you got a bunch of people that work at a corporation.
And if the president of that corporation is an A&M graduate, you get the president.
There you go.
Don't you go down below and go to the third level or the fourth level.
You get the top man.
And I said, number two.
don't get a single soul in here that has any private agenda.
And what we used to say, you get the guy that's pure in heart.
That means his heart's pure, he wants to serve, and he wants to serve because he wants to help the university.
He's paying back.
He's paying back.
And I think if Buck ever thought
And I think maybe he faulted in that school.
And Buck tended to want to get the good old back-slapping sophomore yell leader who'd been to A&M rather than the president of Gulf Hall of Fame.
Now, me personally, if that yell leader still a sophomore was president of Texas Power and Life.
That's different.
That's different.
I take it.
But if he wasn't.
he was named to that board because he was a good old boy, then I think he made a mistake.
And I just don't believe that they're getting into the action.
And I know they're all younger, but we've got younger guys that are up there.
They just are not getting them.
And I don't know whether you can say that's Randy's fault or whether it's a sign of the times.
or whether there's not that interest out there, but I can't believe that's not so.
I believe there's interest there, if you'll just harness it.
I went up one time to Les Potter's office.
Les Potter was president of Lone Star Gas Company in Dallas.
He never been on my association board.
They are getting the kind of leadership that we did back there in the days when the A&M was not quite so large.
I also, in my observer's point of view, feel that the Board of Regents, in some instances...
I feel the same way.
Now, I think that there's been an effort to minimize the
part that the alumni play on the Board of Regents.
I fear you're correct.
That's just like I felt when the accrediting group from the College of Veterinary Medicine came in here and told us we had too many A&M graduates from the College of Veterinary Medicine.
We brought a bunch of people down here from the north that didn't want to work.
And as a result, we went downhill.
Now,
What are we talking about here?
Well, we're talking about the people that deserve great credit.
Let's pick up a fellow named Wayne Stark and bring him in and the role he played.
I can do that.
Please.
Nobody else can do it better than I can.
Wayne Stark, for service that I was,
Wayne Stark applied to be executive secretary of the association when I applied.
Wayne was three years ahead of me, class of 39.
Wayne had been and was working for Anderson Clayton Cotton Company out of Houston.
They gave me the job.
But about the same time this position of Director of the MSC came up.
Was it called that at the time he was appointed?
Yes.
Okay.
And he was named Director of the Memorial Student Center shortly after I was named before either one of us reported.
We both reported to A&M on the same day.
Oh my.
I reported in to McQuillan on October the 1st, 1947.
Wayne reported in to Angel, I guess, or whoever had hired him.
I think it was Angel at the time.
On the same day.
They gave Wayne a house on the campus close to where the MSC was located.
They wouldn't give me a house anywhere because they were trying to move all those houses off the campus.
I was at the groundbreaking.
Wayne and I were very close.
He was doing a lot of the preliminary work for the MSC before they built it.
They broke ground, I believe it was on September the 20th of 1948.
They broke ground for the MSC.
And it took him about two years to build.
So he had nothing to do with the physical design of the building?
No.
That was already done?
That worked.
Well, he got into the picture later on.
Yes, he did.
Mr. Carlton Adams and Brooks Martin and the fellow that was in the Aggieland Orchestra, Wally Scott, up in the system architect's office, designed the MSC.
And Robert McKee, the company out of El Paso, did the work.
They built the building.
Robert E. McKee.
Robert E. McKee.
And they had a big opening of the building.
I think it was in July of 19, June or July of 1948.
They broke it in 1950.
And Ms. Park from San Antonio, I remember, was one of the ladies that spoke.
She represented, she had a son, I think, who was killed in World War II.
And so she spoke because it was a memorial building.
But anyway, Wayne's offices were down at that lower level, far end of the building, and I was next door.
So we were side by side, and I was on his first student council.
of Memorial Student Center Council.
I was on its first council and stayed on that council as long as I was working for the association.
And Wayne and I had a lot of sessions together, cried on each other's shoulders, a lot.
Wayne was a kind of a fella who wouldn't look at the big picture.
In other words, to put it more simply, if elephants were running down the first floor, he'd be down in the basement killing piss ants.
Now that was Wayne's way of doing things.
Pure and hard as he would be, he wanted to do the best he could.
But Wayne was so busy, and I don't want to fault him for this, because it was important for him at the time, particularly important.
trying to further the artwork, and the cultural things, and the dramatic things, rather than fundamental basics of keeping buildings clean.
And as a result, Wayne, in some fashion, has got on Earl's shit face.
And I remember one day, Earl came up.
Wayne came into my office.
He had about a five-page letter.
He said, I want your single space.
And he said, I want you to read this letter before I made it to Pearl.
And I said, all right.
And I read it.
I closed my office door, and I read that letter.
And most of it he was complaining to Earl about the fact that some of his janitors were not performing quite properly.
And I read that letter and I said, my God, I've got to stop this.
So the next morning I got a bill of Wayne to come over and I said, Wayne, first thing let me tell you, don't mail this letter.
I said, keep it one day and then burn it up.
But don't you so show it to anybody else.
I said, let me tell you something.
If there's anything in the world at this moment that Earl doesn't want to see, it's a letter from you complaining about some of the things that you already take care of first.
Don't, for God's sake, send this letter to Earl.
And I said, promise me you won't later.
And he promised he wouldn't.
And two or three days later, I said, why didn't you burn that letter?
I think he said, no.
And I said, get it out of your, get it out, you got it out of your system by writing that letter.
Now get it out of your file so it don't exist.
Then about a year later, I had a call from Earl.
He said, did you go there?
The man in the meeting was Wayne Stark in Beaumont.
I said, yes, sir.
He said, did Wayne badmouth your name at that meeting?
I said, Earl, let me come over and talk to you.
And I went over and I said, Wayne didn't mean to badmouth you.
He was just complaining about some of the things that he felt was going on.
But I said, I don't think he intended to make you look bad if he did.
And he said, well, he did.
He said, I've had four or five phone calls from people who haven't seen me.
And I said, well, Wayne gets carried away on things that he don't have the fitness to get carried away on.
And Earl told me, he said, you tell him to attend to his business and run a clean operation.
Forget about all that stuff.
I said, okay.
Did anybody encourage Wayne, or was it his own self-generation, to be the kind of identifier of student leadership potential?
Because he did it that well to bring these bright kids in.
That was Wayne Stevens.
Okay.
It wasn't anybody else but Wayne.
Wayne, in some way, had the knack, unlike Buck, to pick out these kids that were leaders and did a good job of it.
Have you heard any of the students refer to the green couch treatment?
In his office?
Right.
I can imagine.
Where he lectured to them.
Put them on that old green couch and lectured.
You can do better.
You've got a lot of talent.
Oh, yeah.
Now go use it.
Well, I believe every bit of it.
And he would pick out these kids like John Samuels and Fuller and all the rest of them.
Cloud, and all of them.
And he was performing like a dean of students.
Who hired Hannigan?
Earl Rudder brought Hannigan.
Earl.
Where did he find him, do you know?
He found him just retired as a general.
Yes.
And let's see, he brought him in here, I guess as Commandant first, didn't he or didn't he?
I don't know if it was Commandant or Dean, but it was
He was here when I got here.
He was here when you got here.
When did you come?
He hired Jim Hannigan.
He had known Jim Hannigan during the war.
Oh, okay.
He was familiar with both Doris and Jim.
And he brought him here about the same time he brought John Calhoun and Frank Huber.
I remember snickering one day in a meeting
there'd been too many non-reg students walking across the drill field.
And somebody had come up with the idea to put bailing wire around the trees.
And at this meeting, Hannigan couldn't figure out where anybody could have found the pliers needed to cut the wire.
Cut the wire.
And I said, well, you might look at every pickup on the campus.
Every pickup on the campus.
And he was surprised at that.
One thing about Wayne before I forget.
When Wayne and Earl, or at least Wayne was not in Earl's best of the number one good old boys.
Wayne went to the National Union Building meeting and somebody offered him a job up in Ohio.
And Wayne came to me.
He said, I've been offered this job.
I'm afraid Earl's going to fire me.
And he said, I don't want to turn down the job if Earl's going to fire me.
But if he's not going to fire me, I don't want to leave.
And I said, OK, Earl.
I mean, Wayne, what are you going to do?
He said, I want you to go over and talk to Earl and come back and tell me what he said.
I said, I'll do that.
And I guess Jerry Haught, somebody up there in the president's office, I said, I need to see Earl, but it won't take you for about five minutes and you can work me in.
She came back and said, he'll see you now.
I said, I'm on the way.
Well, I went inside and I said, Earl, my mission is for Wayne Star.
He said, what's Wayne up to now?
I said, well...
Wayne has gone to this national meeting of union directors, and somebody's offered him a job as a union director in a college that's somewhere up in Ohio.
And he thinks you're getting ready to fire him.
And he, if you're gonna terminate him, he wants to take this job.
But if you're not gonna terminate him, he wants to stay here, but he'd like to know kind of what his position is.
And Earl just laughed and said, well, he said, you go over there and tell Blaine that I'm not gonna find him.
But tell Earl from me that I don't want him putting any more naked women's pictures in me.
So Katie Dale, he'll come over and raise hell with me about your naked women.
And tell him to keep the damn place.
clean and tell him to approve the food.
And he just laughed about it.
He said, I'm not going to follow that.
Who were the Mr. Rudders, if he turned to somebody for advice, he turned to you, who else did he?
He turned to McQuillan.
Okay.
McQuillan kept Earl in A&M when he was a student.
McQuillan went to Mr. Irving Aston in Bryan.
Earl needed to borrow money.
And old McQuillan was such a scotchman, he could have loaned him all the money himself.
But he wanted Earl to have the benefit of a banking relationship.
So he called old man Irving and asked him, he said, I'm going to send a young man over to see you.
His name is Earl Runner.
And he said, he needs some money, probably $200.
I don't know what it was.
But anyway, he said, I highly recommend this boy.
And I think he'll pay you back if you'll run with him.
The man asked, Mac told me, the old man asked and said, if you'd recommend him, I'll lend him the money you sent him.
So with that kind of situation, Earl just thought the world of Mac.
Now Mac was highly instrumental in this co-education thing.
Very strong.
And anyway, Earl talked to McQuillan.
He didn't trust Harrington.
He didn't trust Shuffler.
He didn't trust Vi Freeman.
He didn't trust Angel.
And a lot of the stuff that he wanted to find out about, he had asked me to go down there and find out.
I said, I'll go find out.
And when Angel left to go to Arkansas, that's when Earl won out over this conflict.
I had talked to Tom Harrington about taking the job as assistant chancellor that Angel had had.
And I more or less informed him about the job.
I never heard from Tom again, but Earl found out that I had talked to Tom.
Earl called me and he said, I want you in that job.
He said, I want you to take it.
I said, well, I will take it, Earl, if I'm offered the job.
Board of Regents men.
And they were talking to Tom Harrington about who had applied for the job and who he was considering.
And he mentioned my name.
And Earl was apparently present at this meeting.
And Earl called me two or three times that weekend.
That was a Saturday.
He said, they're talking about you for that job.
I want you to take it.
And I said, Earl?
I'm ready to take you, but I have to be offered a job.
I have to be offered.
I had a call from a fellow named Howdy Rideout.
He was a member of the automobile dealership there.
And Howdy said, I understand you were talking about this job with Angel.
I said, I sure am, Howdy.
I applied for the job, and a hotel person sent me for the job.
He said, well, the Board of Regents have talked about you.
They want you in the job.
I said, well, all I need is to be offered the job.
Well, time came and went, I never got offered the job.
Earl called me one day and said, why the hell didn't you take that job?
I said, Earl, the reason I didn't take it, I wasn't offered the job.
And then named Bob Cherry.
And a lot is different because of it.
Yeah, yeah.
So anyway.
I just guess that Tom didn't want me up there.
I think, as a matter of fact, that Tom was a little bit afraid of the former students.
And by the fact that I knew a lot of people among the former students, some of the most powerful ones, that he just was afraid of being a child.
Or maybe he thought, I don't know.
He never discussed it with me.
